text="Deducing Cantor’s theorem à la Lawvere">Deducing <fr:link
type="local"
href="jms-00NF.xml"
addr="jms-00NF"
title="Cantor’s theorem">Cantor’s theorem</fr:link> à la <fr:link
type="local"
href="jms-00NH.xml"
addr="jms-00NH"
title="Lawvere’s fixed point theorem">Lawvere</fr:link></fr:title><fr:date><fr:year>2024</fr:year><fr:month>1</fr:month><fr:day>31</fr:day></fr:date><fr:authors><fr:author><fr:link
type="local"
href="jonmsterling.xml"
addr="jonmsterling"
title="Jon Sterling">Jon Sterling</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>To deduce <fr:ref
addr="jms-00NF"
href="jms-00NF.xml"
taxon="Theorem" /> from <fr:ref
addr="jms-00NH"
href="jms-00NH.xml"
taxon="Theorem" />, we suppose that there is a surjection <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[A\twoheadrightarrow  \mathcal {P}{\mathopen {}\left (A\right )\mathclose {}}]]></fr:tex>; by <fr:ref
addr="jms-00LN"
href="jms-00LN.xml"
taxon="Theorem" />, this is equivalent to saying that we have a surjection <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[e\colon  A\twoheadrightarrow  {\mathopen {}\left (A\to  {\mathopen {}\left  [2\right  ]\mathclose {}}\right )\mathclose {}}]]></fr:tex>. From <fr:ref
addr="jms-00NH"
href="jms-00NH.xml"
taxon="Theorem" />, it follows that <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[{\mathopen {}\left  [2\right  ]\mathclose {}}]]></fr:tex> is a singleton — a contradiction.</fr:p></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree><fr:tree
